AI security is not a neat, one-line definition you can slap on a slide. Depending on who you ask, it means everything from stopping rogue AI agents to policing what your employees paste into ChatGPT.

The reality is simpler, yet chaotic: we now live in a world where every corner of the stack has AI jammed into it, and security teams are scrambling to keep up.

## The Two Sides of AI Security

To keep things simple, we break AI Security into two categories:

### 1. Securing how your people use AI
Employees are throwing sensitive data into ChatGPT, wiring up GitHub Copilot, and tinkering with AI plugins. You can’t write a policy for each shiny new tool. You need visibility, dynamic detection, and automatic enforcement.

### 2. Securing what you build with AI
By 2025, every company should be building with AI. But none of this is immune to risk. Prompt injection, data leakage, hallucinations, and rogue agents are real threats.

{% callout type="note" %}
**The Overlap**: The moment an internal AI app for employee use connects to your knowledge base, these categories merge.
{% /callout %}

## The Confusion in the Market

Vendors muddy the waters by slapping “AI Security” on whatever they’re selling.
- Some do **AI-powered security** (better detection with LLMs).
- Some do **Model Security**.
- Some do **AppSec** for AI.

Prompt Security closes the gap. We provide runtime protection against prompt injection, data leaks, and rogue agent behavior so you can innovate safely.
